<br>
The stupidest thing in this whole EQ debate is the whole risk versus reward argument.  There is no risk in PoP.  The whole concept of risk went out the window a good while back.  What is you enchanters are actually risking?  Are you going to die in some awful place and risk having your corpse and equipment rot?  No, hello graveyard.  Actually corpse rot wasn't that big of a risk anyway.  If you can't find a necromancer or shadowknight given a week's worth of effort ... well that's just sad.  If you die you end up losing experience.  Finding a cleric isn't really that hard either so you probably won't lose that much anyway.  But if you forego waiting for a resurrection that experience is still easily recoverable just given some more time.  Which leads us to the only thing one really loses when you die ... time.  Time to wait for the corpse to pop in the graveyard (but then you weren't actually solo'ing in a spot you couldn't just invis up and drag the corpse to the zone anyway), time to buff and med back up, and then time to recover that lost experience.  So in a sense, risk = waste of time.  But then even with all that wasted time due to the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>enormous</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> risks involved with PoP charm solo'ing you're still getting more experience in the long run than grouping.  So I ask the proponents of this risk versus reward argument, what exactly is this big risk you are taking? <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=359255">Ryenia Skylark</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
